    <title>Combined summary - A Better MMR Definition</title>
    <updated>2023-06-11T21:42:48.896183+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2017-February/013592.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Bitcoin developers are exploring various proposals and solutions to improve the scalability of blockchain transactions. One proposal involves defining a prunable MMR (Modified Merkle Mountain Range) with a specific grammar and structure that allows for pruning of unnecessary data, reducing the size of the blockchain while maintaining its security and integrity. Another proposal involves using UTXO commitments in blocks, which enables actual proofs of non-fraud and lets users prove the validity of a block based on just the previous block.Developers discuss the use of merkle trees as a method for compactly proving the current state of an output and the need for a lookup table from prevouts to TXO tree positions in order to support proofs of non-spend. However, there are issues with updating spent status and cache coherence on updates. The discussion includes proposals for clustering entries by time or using insertion-ordered data structures, as well as the implementation and review of a merkle-set library.Peter Todd's proposals, including his prunable MMR proposal, could help improve the scalability of Bitcoin transactions by reducing the size of the blockchain while maintaining its security and integrity. In email exchanges between Peter Todd and other individuals, they discuss the efficiency of using insertion order as an index, the potential benefits of MMRs for non-existence proofs, and the soundness of proofs in deterministic validation.The email conversation between Bram Cohen and Peter Todd revolves around the benefits of UTXO commitments and Modified Merkle Trees (MMRs) in proving non-fraud and validating blocks. The challenge with UTXO commitments is performance, as the txo set is large and unwieldy, but Cohen argues that appropriate format and implementation tricks can improve performance. Todd questions whether UTXO commitments require random access and proposes an insertion-ordered TXO commitment scheme for better performance.In a series of email exchanges, Bitcoin developers discussed the use of Modified Merkle Trees (MMRs) and Unspent Transaction Output (UTXO) commitments for proving the current state of an output. While Todd argued that MMRs were redundant as blockchain could be used to prove something is in the TXO or STXO set, Cohen believed that UTXO commitments provided benefits for compact proof that something is still in the UTXO set.In an email exchange between Bram Cohen and Peter Todd, they discussed the benefits of using unspent transaction output (UTXO) commitments. Todd proposed committing to the state of all transaction outputs with a merkle tree structure, and suggested committing to an insertion-ordered list indexed by txout # instead of a balanced version of the TXO set. The conversation then shifted to the implementation and review of a merkle-set library, which is deemed complex and lacking sufficient explanation for its advantages. Pieter Wuille discusses the need for a lookup table from prevouts to TXO tree positions in order to support proofs of non-spend, but Bram Cohen counters that this approach falls apart if the goal is to support proofs of non-spend, which is the purpose of the exercise at hand.</summary>
